# API Design Standards

RESTful API design and authentication conventions.

## Hard Requirements

- Do: keep endpoints RESTful and versioned under `/api/<version_number>/`.
- Do: return consistent error envelopes and appropriate HTTP status codes.
- Do: paginate list endpoints.
- Do not: introduce unversioned or ad-hoc response formats.
- Why: predictable contracts reduce client breakage and simplify integrations.

## Opinionated Defaults

- Prefer a typed API framework with schema validation.
- Prefer token-based auth with secure refresh token handling.
- Prefer short-lived access credentials in client memory.
- Prefer auto-generated API documentation for every endpoint set.

## Exceptions

- Public endpoints can skip auth when explicitly documented and rate-limited.
- Internal-only service endpoints can use different auth patterns if security
  review is recorded.

## Acceptance Checks

- API routes are namespaced under `/api/<version_number>/`.
- List endpoints expose pagination metadata.
- Auth flow includes refresh/retry behavior for expiring access tokens.
- API docs can be generated without schema errors.
